			<title>RIFT DPS meter/Timer utility</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?70706-DPS-meter-Timer-utility&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Sun, 20 Feb 2011 01:46:41 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Hey there. 
 
I found this excellent tutorial for setting up ACT with a Rift plugin: 
 
Setup post - long (http://forums.riftgame.com/showthread.php?45549-Advanced-Combat-Tracker-(DPS-Meter-Spell-Timer-etc.)-with-Rift.-ReadItIWorkedHard.). 
 
For those of you that haven't dabbled in EQ2, ACT is a...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- BEGIN TEMPLATE: postbit_external -->
<div>Hey there.<br />
<br />
I found this excellent tutorial for setting up ACT with a Rift plugin:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://forums.riftgame.com/showthread.php?45549-Advanced-Combat-Tracker-(DPS-Meter-Spell-Timer-etc.)-with-Rift.-ReadItIWorkedHard." target="_blank">Setup post - long</a>.<br />
<br />
For those of you that haven't dabbled in EQ2, ACT is a combat log parser on steroids. You can set up various triggers, see your damage in neat charts, configure timers etc. etc.<br />
It does a LOT of things - but mostly it provides a handy DPS overlay meter and parsing tool.<br />
<br />
I am by no means a proponent of &quot;the meter&quot; - I'm the raid leader who screams at the meter-focused numbnuts to move out of the fire.<br />
It is, however, a good way of analyzing your own performance and whatnot - figure out what your miss percentages are and so forth.<br />
<br />
It is also pretty handy for tracking some buffs and cooldowns - Riftstalkers, for example, have three defensive buffs that absolutely need to be up 24/7. <br />
One of them (Phantom Blow) is pretty easy to loose track of in combat since the in-game visual is pretty small, and you don't want 6% damage reduction to drop off - ever :D<br />
You can set up an ACT timer to track it - it only does static-sized buff tracking, so buffs with variable length are a no-go.<br />
Edit: It doesn't actually track buffs - it just starts the timer whenever it sees something predefined come up in the combat logs.  <br />
<br />
There is no EULA breakage - ACT is a stand-alone program that every EQ2 raid guild uses to parse combat logs. ALL it does is read the combatlog.txt in your Rift directory - NOTHING else.<br />
As one guy put it - you can even run it with the game turned off, and it'd work :)</div>

 
